ce:section.ce:para:
To assess the identification capability of our prepared fluorescent sensor array in real samples, we selected tap water and pork as representative matrices. In tap water, ten samples were drawn from each of five species of bacteria, with a bacterial concentration of 1.0  × 107 CFU/mL. The results unequivocally demonstrate a 100 % recognition rate for the array (Fig. 7
                        A), indicating its robust performance in real-world water samples. At the same time, under the condition of low concentration of 1.0  × 103 CFU/mL, five individual bacteria and the mixed bacteria of P. aeruginosa and S. aureus were tested as samples, and the results showed that low concentrations of bacteria in tap water can also be detected using fluorescent arrays (Fig. S13). The fluorescence intensity data of five individual bacterial samples in tap water are in the Supplementary Table S3. Subsequently, we conducted tests on pork purchased from a supermarket to evaluate its bacterial content (Fig. 7B). To assess the selectivity of the sensor array towards amidst potential interfering substances in pork, we conducted a comparative analysis. Here, bovine serum albumin (BSA), glucose, Na+ and Cl- are selected as interfering substances. The fluorescence response of the sensor in the presence of each potential interferent was meticulously evaluated. As shown in Fig. 7B, the sensor array can completely distinguish these interfering substances from the five bacteria, indicating that it has excellent anti-interference ability. In addition, five species of bacteria at concentration is 1.0  × 103 CFU/mL, as well as bacteria mixed with P. aeruginosa and S. aureus, were verified, showing that low concentrations of bacteria growing on pork could also be detected (Fig. S14). The fluorescence intensity data of five individual bacterial samples on pork are in the Supplementary Table S4. The jackknifed classification matrix summarizing the results for five bacteria revealed an impressive recognition rate of 100 % (Table 1
                        ). This underscores the practical potential of our proposed fluorescent sensor array in real-world applications, particularly in the context of food safety and quality control. The outcomes presented in Fig. 7 affirm the efficacy of the fluorescent sensor array in real sample scenarios, demonstrating its high recognition rates and suggesting its suitability for practical applications in diverse settings.
